    {
      "id": "b58f0d71c17a3751448a20fe8ff46aabfea9b071",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-13 08:04:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI guess this is another case of not having consistent exit path where everybody would jump to in case of an error.\n\nWould be better if it was recoded in a way that there is and exit_error (not necessary this exact name) label where we'd jump to on error after request creation?\nThen convert the two returns that also clear a request to GOTO there.\n\nOn the other hand only two such returns might not be all that bad, but probably still better for consistency.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5a5d19ff2619dcc8884cc3af42548335867ea04f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-11-18 07:44:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOleg, I tried the goto-label error handling, which I like in general.  But the result didn't look much neater.  (The major complexity of this function is from \"it\" and \"reqp\", IMHO.)  Can you let current patch go?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
